{"key":"post-13785530","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13785530</id>\n<content>Cubes are not native to California, so no.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A day/night temperature fluctuation is a major pinning trigger, and moist perlite in a shotgun terrarium will not dry out for a month or two, much longer than a cropping cycle.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Standing water is bad, period.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't heat a terrarium.&amp;nbsp; Heat the area it is in if necessary.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, you MUST mist.&amp;nbsp; If you have no evaporation of moisture from your substrate, it won't pin.&amp;nbsp; If you do have evaporation of moisture from your substrate, it will pin, but that lost moisture must be replaced by misting.&amp;nbsp; Spraying the sides of a terrarium is a waste of water.&amp;nbsp; The plastic doesn't need moisture, but the substrate does.&amp;nbsp; New growers obsess on humidity, while &lt;i&gt;loss of&amp;nbsp; moisture&lt;/i&gt; is the number one pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; Every new grower gets this wrong on his first few grows, and they always dispute this fact when it's&amp;nbsp; pointed out to them.&amp;nbsp; Live and learn.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13785739</next>\n<prev>13785342</prev>\n<first>13781137</first>\n<last>17096033</last>\n<when>1295027736</when>\n<utime>01/14/11 07:55 PM</utime>\n</post>"}